message.content: Yes, there are infinitely many odd numbers. The sequence of odd numbers can be represented as \(1, 3, 5, 7, 9, \ldots\), where each term can be expressed as \(2n + 1\) for \(n \in \mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}\). Since \(\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}\) (the set of non-negative integers) is infinite, the set of odd numbers is also infinite.

Yes, there are infinitely many odd numbers. The set of odd numbers can be expressed as \(\{1, 3, 5, 7, 9, \ldots\}\), which is an infinite arithmetic sequence with a common difference of 2. For any natural number \(n\), the number \(2n-1\) is odd, providing a bijection to the natural numbers and thereby demonstrating the infinitude of odd numbers.

Yes, there are infinitely many odd numbers. The set of odd numbers can be defined as the set \(\{2n + 1 \mid n \in \mathbb{Z}\}\), which demonstrates that for every integer \(n\), there corresponds an odd number, and since \(\mathbb{Z}\) is infinite, so is the set of odd numbers.
